{"continue":{"rvcontinue":"20180805105715|853526634","continue":"||"},"warnings":{"main":{"*":"Subscribe to the mediawiki-api-announce mailing list at <https://lists.wikimedia.org/mailman/listinfo/mediawiki-api-announce> for notice of API deprecations and breaking changes. Use [[Special:ApiFeatureUsage]] to see usage of deprecated features by your application."},"revisions":{"*":"Because \"rvslots\" was not specified, a legacy format has been used for the output. This format is deprecated, and in the future the new format will always be used."}},"query":{"normalized":[{"from":"Tom_Rooney_(Florida_politician)","to":"Tom Rooney (Florida politician)"}],"pages":{"19107850":{"pageid":19107850,"ns":0,"title":"Tom Rooney (Florida politician)","revisions":[{"timestamp":"2018-08-23T02:49:08Z","contentformat":"text/x-wiki","contentmodel":"wikitext","*":"{{Other people|Tom Rooney}}\n{{pp-pc1}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|name         = Tom Rooney\n|image        = Tom Rooney.jpg\n|state        = [[Florida]]\n|district     = {{ushr|FL|17|17th}}\n|term_start   = January 3, 2013\n|term_end     = \n|predecessor  = [[Frederica Wilson]]\n|successor    = \n|state1       = [[Florida]]\n|district1    = {{ushr|FL|16|16th}} \n|term_start1  = January 3, 2009\n|term_end1    = January 3, 2013\n|predecessor1 = [[Tim Mahoney]]\n|successor1   = [[Vern Buchanan]]\n|birth_name   = Thomas Joseph Rooney\n|birth_date   = {{birth date and age|1970|11|21}}\n|birth_place  = [[Philadelphia]], [[Pennsylvania]], U.S.\n|death_date   = \n|death_place  = \n|party        = [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]\n|spouse       = Tara Lombardi\n|children     = 3\n|relatives    = [[Art Rooney]] (Grandfather)<br>[[Kate Mara]] (Cousin)<br>[[Rooney Mara]] (Cousin)\n|education    = [[Syracuse University]]<br>[[Washington & Jefferson College]] ([[Bachelor of Arts|BA]])<br>[[University of Florida]] ([[Master of Arts|MA]])<br>[[University of Miami]] ([[Juris Doctor|JD]])\n|website      = {{URL|rooney.house.gov|House website}}\n|allegiance   = {{flagu|United States|1960}}\n|branch       = {{army|United States}}\n|serviceyears = 2000\u20132004 (active)<br>2004\u20132008 (reserve)\n|rank         = {{Dodseal|USAO3-2015|25}} [[Captain (United States O-3)|Captain]]\n|unit         = [[Judge Advocate General's Corps, United States Army|Judge Advocate General's Corps]]\n|mawards      = [[File:Army Commendation Medal ribbon.svg|23px|border]] [[Commendation Medal|Army Commendation Medal]] (2)\n}}\n'''Thomas Joseph Rooney''' (born November 21, 1970) is an [[United States|American]] politician who is the [[United States House of Representatives|U.S. Representative]] for {{ushr|FL|17}}, a post he has held since 2013. He previously represented {{ushr|FL|16}} from 2009 to 2013. He is a member of the [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican Party]].\n\nRooney announced in February 2018 that he is retiring from [[United States Congress|Congress]] and will not seek re-election in [[United States House of Representatives elections in Florida, 2018|2018]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Leary |first=Alex |date=February 19, 2018 |title=Rep. Tom Rooney will not seek re-election |url=http://www.tampabay.com/florida-politics/buzz/2018/02/19/rep-tom-rooney-will-not-seek-re-election/ |work=[[Tampa Bay Times]] |location=Tampa, FL |access-date=February 19, 2018 }}</ref>\n\n==Early life and education==\nRooney was born in Philadelphia, Pennsylvania.<ref name=\"Roll Call\">{{cite news |title=Tom Rooney |url=http://www.rollcall.com/members/29247.html |newspaper=Roll Call |accessdate=15 August 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Tom Rooney|url=https://www.gop.gov/republicans/tomrooney/bio|work=Republicans in Florida|publisher=House Republican Conference|accessdate=29 August 2012}}</ref> When Tom was 14 his father, Patrick J. Rooney Sr., moved to [[Palm Beach Gardens, Florida]] where the family owned a dog track and gambling business.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.nationaljournal.com/almanac/person/tom-rooney-fl/ |title= Rep. Tom Rooney (R-FL, 16th District) |date= 1 July 2011 |newspaper= National Journal |accessdate= 2 September 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url= http://weblogs.sun-sentinel.com/news/politics/palm/blog/2008/07/gambling_money_from_palm_beach.html |title= Gambling money from Palm Beach County at stake in Republican fight for Congress |first= Mark |last= Hollis |date= 17 July 2008 |work= Palm Beach Politics blog |publisher= Scripps Treasure Coast Newspapers |accessdate= 2 September 2012 |quote='Tom Rooney can attempt to run from away from his father's gambling interests all he wants, but at the end of the day the truth is in the money,' said Florida Democratic Party Spokesman Eric Jotkoff.}}</ref> He graduated from the Benjamin School in [[North Palm Beach, Florida]] in 1989.<ref>{{cite news|title=North County Schools:Rep. Tom Rooney to visit The Benjamin School Friday|url=http://www.palmbeachpost.com/news/news/education/north-county-schoolsrep-tom-rooney-to-visit-the--1/nLzXN/|accessdate=29 August 2012|newspaper=Palm Beach Post|date=9 November 2011}}</ref> In college, Rooney played football for [[Syracuse University]] and [[Washington & Jefferson College]] outside of [[Pittsburgh]] where he earned his [[Bachelor of Arts|B.A.]] in [[English Literature]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Washington & Jefferson College counts Super Bowl connections|url=http://www.post-gazette.com/stories/news/education/washington-jefferson-college-counts-super-bowl-connections-283932/|accessdate=29 August 2012|newspaper=Pittsburgh Post-Gazette|date=29 March 2012}}</ref> He was a member of [[Lambda Chi Alpha|Lambda Chi Alpha fraternity]].<ref>{{cite journal|last=Barrick|first=Chris|title=New U.S. Congressman|journal=Cross & Crescent|date=February 2009|volume=XCVI|issue=2|url=http://www.pdf.crossandcrescent.com/2009/02/february2009cc_screen.pdf|accessdate=29 August 2012|format=PDF}}</ref>\n\nRooney attended the [[University of Florida]] where he received his [[Master of Arts|M.A.]] in [[Political science|Political Science]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Political Campaigning Program Alumni|url=http://www.polisci.ufl.edu/campaign/alumni.html|work=Department of Political Science|publisher=University of Florida|accessdate=29 August 2012}}</ref> After that he went to the [[University of Miami School of Law]] where he received his [[Juris Doctor|J.D.]] and met his wife Tara Lombardi.<ref>{{cite web|title=Miami Law Alumnus Marco Rubio, JD '96, Elected U.S. Senator|url=http://www.miami.edu/index.php/news/releases/miami_law_alumnus_marco_rubio_jd_96_elected_us_senator/|work=News Release|publisher=University of Miami|accessdate=29 August 2012|date=3 November 2010|quote=Prior to Rooney's election in 2008, the only other Miami Law alumnus to serve in Congress had been the late Representative Dante Fascell.}}</ref> They became members of [[The Florida Bar]] Association in 1999.\n\nHe is not related to fellow Republican representative [[Francis Rooney]].{{citation needed|date=June 2017}}\n\n==Military career==\nAfter law school, both Rooney and his wife joined the U.S. Army JAG Corps. In 2001, Tom and Tara, along with their newborn son, were stationed at [[Fort Hood]] on [[9/11]]. Rooney spent over four years on Active Duty in the [[Judge Advocate General's Corps (United States Army)|United States Army JAG Corps]]. He served as Special Assistant [[United States Attorney|U.S Attorney]] at Fort Hood in Texas, prosecuting all civilian crimes on post. Rooney also served in the [[1st Cavalry Division (United States)|1st Cavalry Division]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://tomrooney.com/about.php |title=Values |work=Tom Rooney for Congress |accessdate=15 August 2012}}</ref>\n\nIn 2002, Rooney began teaching Constitutional and Criminal Law as an Asst. Prof. in the Dept. of Law at the [[United States Military Academy]] at West Point, New York.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.westpoint.army.mil/about.asp |title=About The Academy |author= |date= |work=United States Military Academy |publisher=U.S. Army |accessdate=16 August 2012}}</ref> He received two [[Army Commendation Medal]]s for his service. Tom and Tara Rooney each completed active duty with the rank of Captain.<ref name=\"Tribune\">{{cite news |title=Military veterans win congressional primaries |first=Howard |last=Altman |url=http://www2.tbo.com/news/politics/2012/aug/14/military-veterans-win-congressional-primaries-ar-464639 |newspaper=Tampa Tribune |date=16 August 2012 |accessdate=16 August 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=A John Paul II Catholic Runs for Office in Florida |first=Deal W. |last=Hudson |url=http://www.crisismagazine.com/2008/a-john-paul-ii-catholic-runs-for-office-in-florida |newspaper=Crisis Magazine |date=13 February 2008 |accessdate=16 August 2012 |quote=I don't think I could run for office without my faith. It's very difficult to put yourself out there. Going to Mass on Sunday is a time for me to get stronger.}}</ref>\n\nDuring his active duty time in the JAG Corps, he served with fellow future Congressman [[Patrick Murphy (Pennsylvania politician)|Patrick Murphy]], a Democrat from Pennsylvania who was the first [[Iraq War]] veteran elected to the U.S. Congress.<ref>{{cite news |title=A Troubling Sign Of Rigid Intolerance |first=Tony |last=Plakas |url=http://articles.sun-sentinel.com/2009-10-21/news/0910200236_1_gays-gender-identity-homosexuality |newspaper=Sun Sentinel |date=21 October 2009 |accessdate=16 August 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Early political career==\nAs his first job out of college, Tom Rooney worked for U.S. Senator [[Connie Mack III]], who had worked with Tom's father, Patrick J. Rooney Sr., at one time. Tom started in Senator Mack's mailroom: \"We opened every letter and that's where I learned what people's issues were. It really helped shape a blank slate in my life.\"<ref name=\"Tribune\"/><ref>{{cite news|last=Rathgeber|first=Bob|title=Connie Mack III mentor to many more than IV|url=http://www.news-press.com/article/20121024/NEWS0107/310240030/0/NEW0119/Connie-Mack-III-mentor-many-more-than-IV|accessdate=24 October 2012|newspaper=News-Press|date=23 October 2012|quote=Rooney, R-Punta Gorda, who is trying to win his third term in Congress in District 17, said Mack is the reason he's a congressman today, planting his political seed two decades ago.}}</ref> After getting his Masters, he returned to Florida, where he went to work as an Assistant Attorney General. While working as a criminal prosecutor for Attorney General [[Charlie Crist]],<ref name=\"Times\">{{cite news |title=Tom Rooney |url=http://www.washingtontimes.com/campaign-2012/candidates/tom-rooney-59163/ |newspaper=Washington Times |accessdate=16 August 2012}}</ref> he joined the Board of Directors with \"The Children's Place at Home Safe,\" a Palm Beach County shelter that helps abused, neglected, and abandoned children. In 2005, Tom was named CEO of Home Safe and because of his work there, Governor [[Jeb Bush]] appointed Rooney to the Children's Services Council of Palm Beach County Board of Directors in January 2006. After his second year as director, Rooney returned to the Board of Directors of Children's Place and resumed his practice of law in [[Stuart, Florida]] with the law firm of Kramer, Sopko & Levenstein, P.A.  He is a graduate of Leadership Palm Beach County.\n\n==U.S. House of Representatives==\n\n===Elections===\n;2008: {{See also|United States House of Representatives elections in Florida, 2008#District 16}}\nRooney challenged Democratic incumbent [[Tim Mahoney]]. Mahoney had narrowly won the Republican-leaning district in 2006, after five-term incumbent [[Mark Foley]] abruptly resigned under a [[Mark Foley scandal|cloud of scandal]].<ref name=\"Times\"/> Since Foley resigned a little more than a month before the election, Florida election law required Foley's name to remain on the general election ballot, with votes for him being transferred to his replacement, State Representative [[Joe Negron]]. It was widely believed that this significantly undermined Negron's chances, as many voters would be reluctant to cast a ballot in Foley's name.<ref>[http://www.foxnews.com/story/0,2933,217258,00.html GOP Picks Negron to Replace Foley on Florida Ballot] ''[[Fox News Channel|FOXnews]]'', October 3, 2006. The campaign used the slogan 'Punch Foley for Negron' as a means of educating the public about the ballot situation and as a means of differentiating the two men, making voting for Foley more palatable.</ref>\n\nGiven Mahoney's narrow margin of victory, coupled with the unusual circumstances surrounding the 2006 election and this district's Republican bent, the 16th District was viewed as one of Republicans' best opportunities to take a congressional seat from the Democrats in 2008.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.tcpalm.com/news/2008/may/03/no-surprises-as-qualifying-closes-for-races/ |title=No surprises as qualifying closes for Congressional races |first=Jim |last=Turner |date=3 May 2008 |work=TCPalm.com |publisher=Scripps Treasure Coast Newspapers |accessdate=16 August 2012 |quote=Considered the only Democratic incumbent in South Florida who might have trouble, Mahoney has seemingly put himself in a good position with his mostly centrist legislative record, having become very accessible to his constituents, and, like other incumbents, bankrolling a sizeable early lead in fundraising among all the candidates.}}</ref> In the Republican Party primary, Rooney was endorsed by Florida's Governor, [[Charlie Crist]], and defeated State Representative [[Gayle Harrell]] and investment banker [[Hal Valeche]]. Mahoney, aided by incumbency and having burnished his image as a moderate [[Blue Dog Democrat]], consistently led Rooney in polls throughout the 2008 election cycle until mid-October 2008,<ref>{{cite news |title=Obama wins Florida en route to White House |first=Larry |last=Copeland |url=https://www.usatoday.com/news/politics/election2008/fl.htm |newspaper=USA Today |date=5 November 2008 |accessdate=14 August 2012 |quote=Republican challenger Tom Rooney, a lawyer and former Army officer, had trailed early in the campaign until news broke last month about Mahoney's affairs. Rooney quickly gained ground and handily won Tuesday night to replace Mahoney representing District 16, covering parts of eight counties from Palm Beach County across the state to the Gulf.}}</ref> when it was revealed that Mahoney, who had promoted a family values image and campaigned against corruption in contrast to the disgraced Foley, had engaged in multiple extramarital affairs and secretly paid off his mistresses to conceal them.<ref>{{cite news |title=Fla. congressman denies breaking any laws |first=Brian |last=Skoloff |url=https://www.usatoday.com/news/politics/2008-10-14-795139830_x.htm |newspaper=USA Today |date=14 October 2008 |accessdate=14 August 2012 |quote=The seat is considered to be one of the more competitive House races, and Mahoney already had a tough challenge in a district that has traditionally leaned slightly Republican. He faces former Army officer Tom Rooney, a lawyer whose family owns the Pittsburgh Steelers.}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=AP: Fla. congressman said to be embroiled in 2nd affair |url=https://www.usatoday.com/news/washington/2008-10-14-mahoney-affair_N.htm |newspaper=USA Today |date=14 October 2008 |accessdate=14 August 2012 |quote=On Tuesday night, a person close to the Mahoney campaign told the AP that Mahoney also was having a relationship with a high-ranking official in Martin County in his Florida district around the same time of the purported affair with Allen.}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Fla's Mahoney drops out of debate over TV presence |first=Brian |last=Skoloff |url=https://www.usatoday.com/news/politics/2008-10-24-3717615975_x.htm |newspaper=USA Today |date=24 October 2008 |accessdate=14 August 2012 |quote=With Mahoney a no-show, Republican challenger Tom Rooney simply took questions during the luncheon held by the nonpartisan Forum Club of the Palm Beaches.}}</ref> This revelation shifted the race decisively in Rooney's favor, even causing the ''[[Palm Beach Post]]'' to take the rare step of rescinding its previous endorsement of Mahoney and endorsing Rooney instead.<ref>{{Citation |last =  Tribune | first = Tampa | title = Tom Rooney Is Best Choice For Republicans In Congressional Primary  |  page = 1 | publisher = Tampa Bay Online  | location = Tampa, FL | date = July 30, 2008 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Scandals dog incumbents in both parties |first1=John |last1=Fritze |first2=Ken |last2=Dilanian |url=https://www.usatoday.com/news/politics/election2008/2008-10-28-campaigncloud_N.htm |newspaper=USA Today |date=28 October 2008 |accessdate=14 August 2012 |quote=Republicans have tread lightly with Florida Democrat Rep. Tim Mahoney, who admitted to having extramarital affairs. Cook predicts the race is likely to be won by his Republican opponent, Tom Rooney.}}</ref>\n\n;2010: {{See also|United States House of Representatives elections in Florida, 2010#District 16}}\nRooney ran unopposed in the Republican primary. In the general election, he defeated Democratic nominee Jim Horn and write-in candidate William Dean.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.tcpalm.com/news/2010/nov/02/republican-tom-rooney-cruising-to-overwhelming/ |title=Republican Tom Rooney cruises to overwhelming win in District 16 U.S. House race |first=Jim |last=Turner |date=2 November 2010 |work=TCPalm.com |publisher=Scripps Treasure Coast Newspapers |accessdate=16 August 2012 |quote=Given a choice of two fiscal conservatives, voters in Florida's 16th Congressional District overwhelmingly kept incumbent Republican Tom Rooney in Washington.}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://elections.msnbc.msn.com/ns/politics/2010/florida |title=Florida results |first=Jim |work=Decision 2010 |publisher=NBC News |accessdate=16 August 2012}}</ref>\n\n;2012: {{See also|United States House of Representatives elections in Florida, 2012#District 17}}\nFor his first two terms, Rooney represented a district stretching from the [[Treasure Coast]] through the Everglades to [[Port Charlotte, Florida|Port Charlotte]] on the other side of the state.  Redistricting, however, saw the 16th renumbered as the [[Florida's 18th congressional district|18th District]] and made significantly more compact.  It lost most of its heavily Republican western portion to the new 17th District, which stretched from the Everglades to the outer suburbs of [[Tampa]].  Rooney opted to run for reelection in the 17th.<ref>{{cite news |title=Race Ratings: Handful of Seats for Grabs After Fla. Reshuffle |first=Joshua |last=Miller |url=http://www.rollcall.com/issues/57_102/Race-Ratings-Handful-of-Seats-for-Grabs-After-Fla-Reshuffle-212763-1.html |date=1 March 2012 |newspaper=Roll Call |accessdate=16 August 2012}}</ref> He retained roughly one-third of his previous constituents.  Most of them lived in the western portion of the old 16th.<ref name=\"Share\">{{cite web |url=http://www.flsenate.gov/PublishedContent/Session/Redistricting/Plans/H000C9047/H000C9047_pop_compare.pdf |title=District by Existing District \u2013 Shares of Population |author=Senate Committee on Reapportionment |date=23 March 2012 |work=Plan H000C9047 |publisher=State of Florida |format=PDF |accessdate=9 August 2012}}</ref><ref name=\"Reshuffle\">{{cite news |title=Are Republicans the winners in district reshuffle involving Allen West, Tom Rooney? |first=George |last=Bennett |url=http://www.palmbeachpost.com/news/news/state-regional/are-republicans-the-winners-in-district-reshuffle-/nL3qR/ |newspaper=Palm Beach Post |date=4 February 2012 |accessdate=12 August 2012 |quote=After months of speculating and strategizing about Florida's new congressional map, it took only two brief phone conversations for Republican U.S. Reps. Tom Rooney and Allen West to dramatically rearrange their political plans.}}</ref>  He sold his home in [[Tequesta, Florida|Tequesta]], which remained in the 18th, and bought a home in [[Okeechobee, Florida|Okeechobee]] as his official residence in the new 17th.\n\nIn the August 14 Republican primary\u2014the real contest in this heavily Republican district\u2014Rooney faced Joe Arnold, a Republican state committeeman for Okeechobee County and member of the school board. Rooney defeated Arnold in a landslide, getting 74% of vote.<ref>{{cite news |title=Incumbent Rooney wins GOP primary in landslide |first=Phil |last=Attinger |url=http://www.newschief.com/article/20120815/NEWS/120819960/ |newspaper=News Chief |date=15 August 2012 |accessdate=15 August 2012 |quote=Rooney collected $930,249 in campaign donations through the last federal finance reporting period, which ended July 25, and had spent $798,006. Arnold raised $13,920 through that same period, and had spent $13,184.}}</ref> Rooney ran in the general election against a retired airline pilot, Democrat William Bronson (formerly an unsuccessful Republican candidate in Massachusetts and Georgia) as well as Socialist Workers Party write-in candidate Tom Baumann (who ran unsuccessful campaigns in Minnesota and in the Borough of Manhattan).<ref>{{cite news |title=Rooney courts new faces in newly drawn district |first=George |last=Bennett |url=http://www.heraldtribune.com/article/20120801/ARCHIVES/208011037/-1/ |newspaper=Sarasota Herald-Tribune |date=1 August 2012 |accessdate=11 August 2012 |quote=...Rooney says he often feels like a political rookie these days as he pursues a third term by introducing himself to new voters in freshly drawn congressional District 17.}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Attinger|first=Phil|title=Incumbent Challenged In Sprawling District|url=http://www.theledger.com/article/20120930/POLITICS/120939945|accessdate=1 October 2012|newspaper=The Ledger|date=30 September 2012|quote=When voters get their ballots for the Nov. 6 election, the U.S. Congressional District 17 will be one of the few in which there will be a three-way race.}}</ref>\n\nRooney received endorsements in Florida from Agriculture Commissioner [[Adam Putnam]], U.S. Sen. [[Marco Rubio]], U.S. Reps. [[Allen West (politician)|Allen West]] and [[Dennis A. Ross]] as well as from the [[National Rifle Association]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Rooney, Arnold vie in new District 17 |first=lois |last=Kindle |url=http://www2.tbo.com/news/politics/2012/aug/11/memeto2-rooney-arnold-vie-in-new-district-17-ar-461018/ |newspaper=Tampa Tribune |date=11 August 2012 |accessdate=11 August 2012 |quote=The two Republicans vying to represent congressional District 17 couldn't be more different, giving voters a clear choice in next week's primary. }}</ref> In their Saturday, October 13, edition the ''[[Tampa Bay Times]]'' recommended Tom Rooney for the District 17 seat, and on October 19, ''[[The Tampa Tribune]]'' endorsed him.<ref>{{cite news|title=For U.S. House of Representatives|url=http://www.tampabay.com/opinion/editorials/article1256047.ece|accessdate=12 October 2012|newspaper=Tampa Bay Times|date=13 October 2012|quote=Rooney, 41, is not an ideal choice. He backs the House Republican budget that would cut taxes and spending but not raise additional revenue. His call to repeal health care reform suggests he is in denial about the concerns of 4 million Floridians who have no health insurance. But Rooney is more reasonable in calling for an end to some tax loopholes and in being open to creating a path to obtaining legal status\u2014but not citizenship\u2014for some illegal immigrants.}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Our choices for Congress|url=http://www2.tbo.com/news/opinion/2012/oct/19/naopino1-our-choices-for-congress-ar-537665/|work=Tampa Bay Online|publisher=Tampa Media Group|accessdate=19 October 2012|date=19 October 2012|quote=He may be new to Hillsborough, but we expect voters who get to know him will appreciate Rooney's experience and sensible priorities.}}</ref> ''[[The Bradenton Herald]]'' recommended Rooney on 26 October.<ref>{{cite news|title=In U.S. House race, Tom Rooney's support of agriculture serves East Manatee interests|url=http://www.bradenton.com/2012/10/26/4252971/in-us-house-race-tom-rooneys-support.html|accessdate=28 October 2012|newspaper=Bradenton Herald|date=26 October 2012|quote=As a member of the House Agriculture Committee and chair of the Subcommittee on Livestock, Dairy and Poultry, the 41-year-old Rooney sits in a strong position to bolster Florida's farms and ranches and the rural communities in East Manatee. Indeed, the entire district is one of the largest agriculture producing regions in the country, with dairy, citrus, beef, fruit and vegetable farms.}}</ref>\n;2014: {{See also|United States House of Representatives elections in Florida, 2014#District 17}}\n;2016: {{See also|United States House of Representatives elections in Florida, 2016#District 17}}\n\n===Tenure===\nOne of the first bills Rooney introduced in the House was to prevent any money being spent to bring prisoners to Florida from the [[Guantanamo Bay detention camp]]. Another was a bill he co-sponsored to try to reduce the number of military veteran suicides by mandating mental health screenings for returning troops. Although that bill did not pass, the military eventually adopted the reforms Rooney asked for.<ref name=\"Times\"/><ref>{{cite web|last=Samples|first=Eve|title=Veterans suicide crisis defies party lines|url=http://www.tcpalm.com/news/2012/sep/27/eve-samples-suicide-an-enemy-military-has-yet-to/|date=27 September 2012|work=TCPalm|publisher=The E.W. Scripps Company|accessdate=28 September 2012|quote=July marked the worst month on record for Army suicides, and the numbers are similarly bleak across other branches of the military.}}</ref> Rooney has been recognized by the city of Stuart, Florida for his efforts to prevent veteran suicides.<ref name=\"Mattise\">{{cite web|last=Mattise|first=Jonathan|title=Rooney recognized in Stuart for work with veterans suicide prevention, gives insight on various topics|url=http://www.tcpalm.com/news/2012/sep/25/rooney-recognized-in-stuart-for-work-with-gives/|work=TCPalm|publisher=The E.W. Scripps Company|accessdate=28 September 2012|date=25 September 2012}}</ref>\n\nRooney sponsored a bill to name a federal courthouse under construction in [[Fort Pierce, Florida|Fort Pierce]] in honor of a St. Lucie County [[Adams Ranch|rancher]], and former Florida Supreme Court Chief Justice, Alto Lee Adams Sr.; Rooney's bill was approved by the House in September 2009, but was not passed by the Senate until September 2012, when the new courthouse had been open for eight months.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.tcpalm.com/news/2012/sep/22/us-senate-approves-naming-federal-courthouse-lee/|title=U.S. Senate approves naming federal courthouse after late Alto Lee Adams Sr.|date=22 September 2012|work=TCPalm.com |publisher=Scripps Treasure Coast Newspapers |accessdate=25 September 2012 |quote=Supported in the Senate by Florida Democrat Bill Nelson, it passed unanimously Saturday and now heads to the president for his signature.}}</ref>\n\nSince 2009, Rooney has personally presented [[Congressional Award]] medals to young people in his district.<ref>{{cite web|title=July 2009 \u2013 January 2010|url=http://www.congressionalaward.org/newsletters/2010jan.php|work=Newsletter|publisher=The Congressional Award|accessdate=12 October 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=2 LP High students earn Congressional Award|url=http://www2.highlandstoday.com/news/highlands-news/2010/apr/07/la-2-lp-high-students-earn-congressional-award-ar-320448/|first=Marc|last=Valero|work=Highlands Today|publisher=Tampa Media Group|accessdate=12 October 2012|date=7 April 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Congressional Award medals bestowed on 58 Palm Beach County school students by Rep. Tom Rooney|url=http://www.wptv.com/dpp/news/congressional-award-medals-bestowed-on-58-palm-beach-county-school-students-by-rep.-tom-rooney-|work=WPTV|publisher=E.W. Scripps|accessdate=12 October 2012|date=17 October 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=2 Storm Players Earn Congressional Award Gold Medals|url=http://www.stormlacrosse.org/Default.asp|work=Storm Lacrosse|publisher=LeagueAthletics.com|accessdate=12 October 2012|date=13 November 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Hughes|first=Kim|title=Local students given Congressional Awards by U.S. Rep. Tom Rooney|url=http://www.tcpalm.com/news/2012/apr/28/local-students-given-congressional-awards-by-us/|work=TCPalm|publisher=E.W. Scripps|accessdate=12 October 2012|date=28 April 2012|quote=Rooney congratulated all the students, noting Florida led the nation this year in Congressional gold medalists, with a total of 280.}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2011, House Speaker [[John Boehner]], R-Ohio, traveled to Iraq with Rooney and four other members, who met with Prime Minister [[Nouri al-Maliki]] and Ambassador [[James Franklin Jeffrey]]. Rooney said that they discussed with Maliki how the United States and Iraq might interact diplomatically after the U.S. troop withdrawal scheduled for December of that year.<ref>{{cite web | url= http://www.lvrj.com/blogs/politics/Reid_Heck_on_travel_overseas.html |title= Reid, Heck on travel overseas |last= Tetreault |first= Steve |date= 18 April 2011 |work= The Political Eye (blog) |publisher= Las Vegas Review-Journal |accessdate= 14 August 2012}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Evans Crary Sr House, Downtown, Stuart, Florida 1021.JPG|200px|thumb|right|Stuart, Florida office of Congressman Tom Rooney]]\nOn the evening of February 19, 2012, a man crashed his pickup truck into Rooney's Stuart, Florida office. No one was inside the building at the time. The man claimed he tried to park in front of the building, but instead of pressing the brake, accidentally pressed the accelerator. The driver was cited for careless driving by the Stuart Police Department.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.wpbf.com/Pickup-Truck-Crashes-Into-Congressman-s-Stuart-Office/-/8789538/9243600/-/10mt32jz/-/index.html |title=Pickup Truck Crashes Into Congressman's Stuart Office |date=20 February 2012 |work=WPBF-TV |publisher=Hearst Television Inc |accessdate=8 August 2012 |quote=The truck went completely inside the building and had to be towed from the scene.}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Pickup Truck Crashes into U.S. Rep. Tom Rooney's Stuart Office |first=Jim |last=Turner |url=http://www.sunshinestatenews.com/blog/pickup-truck-crashes-rooney's-stuart-office |newspaper=Sunshine State News |date=20 February 2012 |accessdate=8 August 2012 |quote=The office of the Tequesta Republican wasn't occupied until the pickup truck entered the building.}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Car crashes into congressman's office |first=Judy |last=Kurtz |url=http://washingtonscene.thehill.com/in-the-know/36-news/14199-judy-kurtz |newspaper=The Hill |date=22 February 2012 |accessdate=8 August 2012 |quote=If you're having a crummy day, here's a friendly reminder that it could always be worse: at least a truck didn't crash straight into your office.}}</ref>\n\nRooney, as Chairman of the House Agriculture Subcommittee on Livestock, Dairy and Poultry, introduced The Defense of Environment and Property Act in March 2012. This act would make changes to federal water regulations and prevent some prosecutions of farmers and landowners by the [[United States Environmental Protection Agency]] and the [[United States Army Corps of Engineers]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://rooney.house.gov/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=3377|title=Rooney Introduces Defense of Environment and Property Act|date =30 March 2012|work=Press Release|publisher =Congressman Thomas J. Rooney Website|accessdate=21 August 2012}}</ref> In response to an expansion of federal power to regulate wetlands in a 2011 EPA and Army Corps document that redefined \"navigable waters,\" the Rooney bill defines navigable waters to exclude \"wetlands without a continuous surface connection\" to a body of water. The Rooney bill is a companion to a Senate bill introduced by Rand Paul.<ref>{{cite news|last=VerBruggen|first=Robert|title=The Next Step for the Sacketts|url=http://www.nationalreview.com/articles/294488/next-step-sacketts-robert-verbruggen|accessdate=24 September 2012|newspaper=National Review Online|date=27 March 2012|quote=In a concurrence in last week's Supreme Court decision, Justice Samuel Alito took the somewhat unusual step of calling out Congress for its vague language, encouraging the legislative branch to clarify the Clean Water Act.}}</ref>\n\n====Libya====\nA June 2011 bill to defund [[2011 military intervention in Libya|U.S. operations in Libya]] was written by Rooney, but defeated on the floor of the House because 89 Republicans voted against it. Rooney accepted responsibility for defeat of the bill, which was in competition with a non-binding resolution to deny President [[Barack Obama]] authority to wage war against Libya, saying \"It was my bill. You can blame me. I think we tried to limit funds so our kids weren't in harm's way but not leave [[NATO]] on their own. People either wanted all or they wanted nothing.\"<ref>{{cite news|last=Cassata|first=Donna|title=Libya Resolution: House Rejects Measures To Authorize Libya Mission, Cut Off Funding|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2011/06/24/libya-resolution-authorization-house-vote_n_883946.html|accessdate=25 September 2012|newspaper=Huffington Post|date=24 June 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Pergram|first=Chad|title=Rooney Takes Blame for Failed Vote to Defund Libya Operation|url=http://politics.blogs.foxnews.com/2011/06/24/rooney-takes-blame-failed-vote-defund-libya-operation|accessdate=25 September 2012|newspaper=FOX News Network|date=24 June 2011|quote=It is rare on Capitol Hill for a lawmaker to concede something didn't go as planned.}}</ref>\n\nOn 13 September 2012, Rooney said that Obama should be blamed for [[2012 diplomatic missions attacks|attacks on U.S. embassies]] in the [[Middle East]] because the violence, and the deaths of four Americans in the [[U.S. Consulate attack in Benghazi]], was foreseeable: \"We supported the rebels without taking into account their individual values or motives, and without understanding their ability or plan to govern. We helped these individuals topple a dictator, but then stood on the sidelines as radical extremists assumed power. It should come as no surprise that these movements in the region have given way to violent, anti-American actions.\"<ref>{{cite news|last=Allen|first=Jonathan|title=Tom Rooney blames Obama for Libya violence|url=http://www.politico.com/news/stories/0912/81180.html|accessdate=25 September 2012|newspaper=Politico|date=13 September 2012|quote=Increasingly, Republicans have criticized Obama for what they portray as a failure to lead in the region, and Rooney's are among the harshest attacks yet.}}</ref>\n\n====District switch with Allen West====\nAlthough most of the voters in Rooney's old 16th District were in the new 18th District, in January 2012 Rooney announced that he would run for the neighboring 17th Congressional District seat, while Allen West declared in the new 18th.  Redistricting had made West's old 22nd District, which already had a modest Democratic lean, even more Democratic, and West wanted to run in a friendlier district.<ref name=\"Share\"/><ref>{{cite news |title=Allen West is walking on sunshine |first=Alex |last=Isenstadt |url=http://www.politico.com/news/stories/0112/72247.html |newspaper=Politico |date=31 January 2012 |accessdate=12 August 2012 |quote=The switch comes after a wave of conservative outrage at the proposed redistricting plan, with some accusing Republicans in the state Legislature of trying to push West, a bombastic freshman who has clashed with the party's leadership, out of Congress.}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=In Florida: Anger, Confusion, Musical Chairs |first=Stuart |last=Rothenberg |url=http://www.rollcall.com/issues/57_91/florida_anger_confusion_musical_chairs_allen_west_patrick_murphy-212166-1.html |newspaper=Roll Call |date=7 February 2012 |accessdate=16 August 2012}}</ref>  As previously mentioned, Rooney's former district had been made somewhat friendlier to Democrats, and he opted to run in a more conservative district that included a large chunk of his old district's western portion.\n\nIn announcing his decision to run for reelection in Rooney's Congressional district, Allen West said:\n\n<blockquote>I have always believed the state of Florida would be best served by having both Congressman Tom Rooney and myself in the House of Representatives working to solve our nation's most pressing problems.  I have never wavered from my vision; to work to create jobs, restrain federal government spending, reduce America's ever increasing national debt, and provide for a strong national defense to ensure a safer and more prosperous future for our children and grandchildren. Congressman Rooney is a statesman and has been an honorable public servant to the constituents of Florida's 16th Congressional district.  It is my goal to continue the success Congressman Rooney has had in Florida's 16th Congressional district in the newly proposed 18th district.<ref>{{cite news |title=West switching districts |first=David |last=Catanese |url=http://www.politico.com/blogs/david-catanese/2012/01/west-switching-districts-113015.html |newspaper=Politico |date=31 January 2012 |accessdate=12 August 2012}}</ref></blockquote>\n\n====Committee assignments====\n* '''[[United States House Committee on Agriculture|Committee on Agriculture]]'''\n** [[United States House Agriculture Subcommittee on Livestock, Dairy, and Poultry|Subcommittee on Livestock, Dairy, and Poultry]] (Chairman)\n** [[United States House Agriculture Subcommittee on Nutrition and Horticulture|Subcommittee on Nutrition and Horticulture]]\n* '''[[United States House Committee on Armed Services|Committee on Armed Services]]'''\n** [[United States House Armed Services Subcommittee on Tactical Air and Land Forces|Subcommittee on Tactical Air and Land Forces]]\n** [[United States House Armed Services Subcommittee on Military Personnel|Subcommittee on Military Personnel]]\n** [[United States House Armed Services Subcommittee on Oversight and Investigations|Subcommittee on Oversight and Investigations]]\n* '''[[United States House Permanent Select Committee on Intelligence|Permanent Select Committee on Intelligence]]\n* '''[[Republican Study Committee]]'''<ref>{{cite web|title=Member List|author=|url=https://rsc-walker.house.gov/|format=|publisher=Republican Study Committee|date=|accessdate=2 January 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Caucus memberships===\n* [[Congressional Arts Caucus]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Membership|author=|url=https://artscaucus-slaughter.house.gov/membership|format=|publisher=Congressional Arts Caucus|date=|accessdate=13 March 2018}}</ref>\n*[[United States Congressional International Conservation Caucus]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Our Members|author=|url=https://royce.house.gov/internationalconservation/members.html|publisher=U.S. House of Representatives International Conservation Caucus |date=|accessdate=5 August 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Political positions==\nRooney has a score of 71% from [[Heritage Action for America]] regarding his conservative voting record, which is above the Republican House average.<ref name=\"HAS\">{{cite web|title=Heritage Action Scorecard|url=https://www.heritageactionscorecard.com/members/member/R000583|website=Heritage Action Scorecard|publisher=Heritage Action for America|accessdate=24 December 2017}}</ref>\n\nRooney favors agricultural subsidies, including [[crop insurance]] and sugar price supports, so that food production in this country can better compete with other countries that provide government subsidies to their farmers. Rooney explained that \"I don't want our country to depend on Mexico for our food, and I don't want Florida to lose agriculture jobs that we really need.\"<ref name=\"Mattise\"/><ref>{{cite web|last=Samples|first=Eve|title=We all pay for sugar price supports\u2014and the St. Lucie River pays, too|url=http://www.tcpalm.com/news/2012/sep/30/eve-samples-we-all-pay-for-sugar-price-supports/|work=TCPalm.com|publisher=The E.W. Scripps Company|accessdate=1 October 2012|date=30 September 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Samples|first=Eve|title=With faceless culprits, to whom can we appeal to stop pollution of St. Lucie River? Here's a list|url=http://www.tcpalm.com/news/2012/oct/11/eve-samples-with-faceless-culprits-who-can-we-to/|work=TCPalm.com|publisher=The E.W. Scripps Company|accessdate=11 October 2012|date=11 October 2012}}</ref>\n\n===F-35 alternative engine===\n[[File:Sdd f136 006.jpg|thumb|GE/Rolls-Royce engine for F-35]]\nRooney fought to remove spending for an alternate engine program (built by [[GE Aviation]] and [[Rolls-Royce plc]]) for the [[F-35 Joint Strike Fighter]]. [[The Pentagon]] had already taken the position that having a single contractor ([[Pratt & Whitney]]) will save money. \"The Pentagon has said repeatedly that they do not want it and do not need it, and the American taxpayers certainly cannot afford it,\" Rooney said.<ref>{{cite news |url= http://www.washingtontimes.com/news/2011/feb/16/house-breaks-old-taboos-in-cutting-spree/ |title= House breaks old taboos in cutting spree |last= Dinan |first= Stephen |date= 16 February 2011 |newspaper= Washington Times |accessdate= 16 August 2012}}</ref>\n\nRooney sponsored an amendment to the 2012 House spending bill to end funding for the extra engine of the F-35 Joint Strike Fighter, which passed with support from freshman members of the [[Tea Party Caucus]].<ref>{{cite news |url= http://www.defensepolicy.org/2011/congressman-tom-rooney/congressman-tom-rooney-defund-the-jsf-alternate-engine |title= Defund the JSF Alternate Engine |last= Rooney |first= Tom |date= 21 February 2011 |newspaper= DefensePolicy.org |accessdate= 29 August 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Tom Rooney (R-Fla.)|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/tom-rooney-r-fla/gIQADjiUAP_topic.html|work=WP Politics|publisher=Washington Post|accessdate=29 August 2012|first=Greg|last=Sargent|date=24 July 2012}}</ref>  In December 2011 GE abandoned self-funding to continue development of its alternate engine, finally ending the project. Rooney said that the decision by GE \"will finally remove any risk that taxpayers may be saddled with the costs of sustaining an extra engine in the future.\"<ref>{{cite news |url= https://finance.yahoo.com/news/GE-Aviation-ends-F-35-fighter-apf-3630210224.html |title= GE Aviation ends F-35 fighter engine development |last= Sewell |first= Dan |date= 2 December 2011 |newspaper= Yahoo! Finance |accessdate= 29 August 2012}}</ref>\n\n===Terrorism===\nRooney criticised [[Justin Amash]] in May 2012, accusing the Michigan Republican of wanting to \"coddle foreign enemy combatants\" because he proposed an amendment to the [[National Defense Authorization Act]] (NDAA) to stop the military from indefinitely detaining suspected terrorists who were caught in the United States. Amash and Congressman [[Adam Smith (politician)|Adam Smith]] said they worried about civil liberties and the constitutionality of allowing indefinite detention of U.S. residents suspected of being terrorists.<ref>{{cite news |url= http://politics.heraldtribune.com/2012/05/17/area-congressman-debates-how-to-treat-suspected-terrorists/ |title= Area congressman debates how to treat suspected terrorists |last= Wallace |first= Jeremy |date= 17 May 2012 |newspaper= Sarasota Herald-Tribune |accessdate= 30 August 2012 |quote=Rooney later took to the House floor to argue in support of another amendment he proposed that would force suspected foreign terrorists and enemy combatants to be tried by a military commission in Guantanamo Bay in Cuba instead of in U.S. courts.}}</ref> A Rooney press release said that \"the Amash amendment sacrifices our national security in order to coddle foreign enemy combatants. Never in our nation's history have we granted enemy combatants who attack our homeland during a time of war the same rights and privileges of American citizens, but that's exactly what the Amash amendment would do.\"<ref>{{cite news |url= http://www.rollcall.com/news/tom_rooney_accuses_justin_amash_of_coddling_terrorists-214629-1.html |title= Tom Rooney Accuses Justin Amash of Coddling Terrorists |last= Stanton |first= John |date= 17 May 2012 |newspaper= Roll Call |accessdate= 16 August 2012 |quote=Rooney, a former military prosecutor, ripped into his colleague as the House prepared to debate Amash's bipartisan amendment to the defense reauthorization bill that would eliminate the authority of the military to indefinitely detain individuals suspected of being terrorists who were caught within the United States.}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url= http://rooney.house.gov/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=3393 |title= Amash Amendment Rewards al Qaeda Attacks on U.S. Soil |date= 17 May 2012 |work= Press Release |publisher= Congressman Thomas J. Rooney Website |accessdate= 30 August 2012}}</ref> Rooney's press release was criticised in turn by a statement from [[Ron Paul]]'s [[Campaign for Liberty]] which accused Rooney of being \"disgracefully dishonest.\"<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.campaignforliberty.org/profile/7786/blog/2012/05/17/disgracefully-dishonest |title= Representative Rooney's Disgracefully Dishonest Release |date= 17 May 2012 |work= Blog |publisher= Campaign for Liberty |accessdate= 30 August 2012 |quote=...Congressmen like Tom Rooney would seek to turn the judicial system on its head.}}</ref>\n\nFinally, Rooney issued a statement of support for a competing amendment to the NDAA by congressmen [[Jeff Landry]], [[Louie Gohmert]] and [[Scott Rigell]]: \"The Landry/Gohmert/Rigell amendment explicitly re-affirms and protects the constitutional rights of American citizens, and states clearly that no citizens' constitutional rights can be denied under the provisions of the defense bill... While it's critical that we protect the rights of American citizens, we should absolutely not exploit legitimate concerns in a misguided effort to extend our rights and privileges to foreign terrorists who attack our homeland.\" The Amash/Smith amendment was defeated and the  Landry/Gohmert/Rigell amendment was adopted, both by large margins.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.motherjones.com/kevin-drum/2012/05/republicans-ndaa-detention-terrorist |title= House GOP Kills Proposal to Block Indefinite Detention of US Citizens |last= Drum |first= Kevin |date= 18 May 2012 |newspaper= Mother Jones |accessdate= 30 August 2012 |quote=...when Republicans like Rooney say that Smith and Amash want to \"coddle terrorists,\" they're not necessarily talking about some heavily armed Al Qaeda fighter in Kandahar. They're potentially talking about you.}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url= http://gohmert.house.gov/news/documentsingle.aspx?DocumentID=296195 |title= Rep. Gohmert's Amendment to the NDAA Adopted |date= 18 May 2012 |work= Press Release |publisher= Congressman Louie Gohmert Website |accessdate= 30 August 2012}}</ref>\n\n===Muslim Brotherhood controversy===\nOn June 13, 2012, Rooney was one of five members of Congress (including [[Michele Bachmann]], [[Trent Franks]], [[Louie Gohmert]] and [[Lynn Westmoreland]]) to send letters to the Inspectors General<ref>{{cite web |url=http://bachmann.house.gov/news/documentsingle.aspx?DocumentID=303218 |title=House Members Seek National Security Answers|date=13 June 2012 |work= Press Release |publisher= Congresswoman Michele Bachmann Website |accessdate=23 August 2012}}</ref> of the Office of the Director of National Intelligence, the Department of Defense, the Department of Homeland Security, the Department of Justice and the Department of State seeking investigations into what they claimed was the U.S. government's involvement with the [[Muslim Brotherhood]].\n\nOne of the letters in particular to Ambassador Harold W. Geisel, the Deputy [[Inspector General]] of the [[United States Department of State]], used the Department's Deputy [[Chief of Staff]], [[Huma Abedin]], as an example of the undue influence. The letter said that Abedin \"has three family members\u2013her late father, her mother and her brother\u2013connected to Muslim Brotherhood operatives and/or organizations,\" referring to a study by the [[Center for Security Policy]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://bachmann.house.gov/uploadedfiles/ig_letter_dept_of_state.pdf |title=Letter to the Deputy Inspector General |author= |date=13 June 2012 |format=PDF |publisher=Congress of the United States |accessdate=19 July 2012 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120719054658/http://bachmann.house.gov/uploadedfiles/ig_letter_dept_of_state.pdf |archivedate=19 July 2012 |df= }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Cordes|first=Nancy|title=Michele Bachmann refuses to back down on claims about Huma Abedin|url=http://www.cbsnews.com/8301-505267_162-57475483/michelle-bachmann-refuses-to-back-down-on-claims-about-huma-abedin/|accessdate=19 July 2012|newspaper=CBS This Morning|date=19 July 2012 |quote=Bachmann, from Minnesota, and the four other representatives sent letters to top intelligence and security officials last week warning that the Muslim Brotherhood, a global religious Islamic movement whose members have been linked to terrorist groups in the past, may have infiltrated the top levels of U.S. government.}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://muslimbrotherhoodinamerica.com/key-findings/ |title=Key Findings |last=Gaffney |first=Frank |date= |work=The Muslim Brotherhood in America |publisher=Center for Security Policy |accessdate=11 August 2012 |quote=Notably, six Islamist-sympathizers have achieved positions within or advisory roles serving Team Obama:  Special Envoy to the Organization of Islamic Cooperation Rashad Hussein; Deputy Chief of Staff to Secretary of State Hillary Clinton Huma Abedein; Presidential advisor Dalia Mogahed; FBI Citizens Academy graduate Kifah Mustafa; Homeland Security Advisory Committee Member Mohamed Elibiary and Homeland Security Countering Violent Extremism Working Group Member Mohamed Magid.}}</ref>\n\nRepublican Senators [[John McCain]], [[Lindsey Graham]], and [[Scott Brown (politician)|Scott Brown]], as well as Bachmann's former campaign chief [[Ed Rollins]] defended Abedin against these allegations.<ref>{{cite news|last=Rollins|first=Edward|title=Bachmann's former campaign chief \u2013 shame on you, Michele |url=http://www.foxnews.com/opinion/2012/07/18/bachmann-former-campaign-chief-shame-on-michele/|publisher=FoxNews|accessdate=24 July 2012|date=18 July 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Terkel|first=Amanda|title=John McCain Slams Michele Bachmann's 'Unfounded' Attacks On Huma Abedin, Muslim-Americans|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2012/07/18/john-mccain-michele-bachmann-muslim_n_1683277.html|publisher=Huffington Post|accessdate=19 July 2012|date=18 July 2012}}</ref>\nSpeaker of the House [[John Boehner]] told reporters: \"I don't know Huma. But from everything that I do know of her, she has a sterling character, and I think accusations like this being thrown around are pretty dangerous.\"<ref>{{cite news|last=O'Keefe|first=Ed|title=John Boehner: Accusations against Huma Abedin 'pretty dangerous'|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/2chambers/post/john-boehner-accusations-against-huma-abedin-pretty-dangerous/2012/07/19/gJQAeDT6vW_blog.html|accessdate=19 July 2012|newspaper=Washington Post|date=19 July 2012}}</ref> Congressman [[Mike Simpson]] condemned the letter as a revival of [[McCarthyism]], telling the ''[[Idaho Statesman]]'': \"Unfortunately, it's not just Michele. The public says, 'There go those Republicans again.' It's a bad reflection on all Republicans. I can't believe the other four members she got to sign the letter with her. Amazing... That doesn't reflect the House Republican Caucus.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://voices.idahostatesman.com/2012/08/10/idahopolitics/idahos_rep_simpson_says_michele_bachmann_reviving_mccarthyism_ta |title=Idaho's Rep. Simpson says Michele Bachmann reviving McCarthyism 'outrageous,' tainting all Republicans |last=Popkey |first=Dan |date=10 August 2012 |work=Idaho Politics's Blog |publisher=Idaho Statesman |accessdate=11 August 2012 |quote=Seven-term GOP Rep. Mike Simpson said Friday that Rep. Michele Bachmann's claim that an extremist Islamic group has infiltrated the U.S. government is a revival of McCarthyism that must be condemned.}}</ref>\n\nAn editorial in [[Scripps Treasure Coast Newspapers]] also brought up the ghost of McCarthyism, explicitly pronouncing disappointment in Rooney.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.tcpalm.com/news/2012/aug/09/editorial-rooneys-involvement-in-islamist-scare/ |title=Rooney's involvement in Islamist scare-mongering out of character, disappointing  |author=Editorial Board |date=9 August 2012 |work=TCPalm.com |publisher=Scripps Treasure Coast Newspapers |accessdate=11 August 2012 |quote=It's difficult to imagine U.S. Rep. Tom Rooney associating himself with the ranting of former presidential candidate Michele Bachmann, his House colleague.}}</ref> On the other hand, Newt Gingrich argued in favor of investigation into the Muslim Brotherhood, characterizing Rooney and the rest as the \"National Security Five.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.politico.com/news/stories/0712/79104.html |title=In defense of Michele Bachmann, Muslim Brotherhood probes |last=Gingrich |first= |last2=Newt |date=29 July 2012 |work=Opinion Contributor |publisher=Politico |accessdate=11 August 2012 |quote=The underlying driving force behind this desperate desire to stop unpleasant questions is the elite's fear that an honest discussion of radical Islamism will spin out of control. They fear if Americans fully understood how serious radical Islamists are, they would demand a more confrontational strategy.}}</ref> Columnist [[Cal Thomas]] shrugged off the specter of McCarthyism, and said that the real possibility of infiltration by Islamic extremists deserves to be investigated.<ref>{{cite news |title=Suppose Michele Bachmann is right? |first=Cal |last=Thomas |url=http://www.thestate.com/2012/07/29/2371334/thomas-suppose-michele-bachmann.html |newspaper=[[The State (newspaper)|The State]] |date=29 July 2012 |accessdate=11 August 2012 |quote=Like the ghosts of Shakespeare's Banquo or Dickens' Jacob Marley, the specter of the late commie-hunting congressman from Wisconsin, Joseph McCarthy, will always be with us. It is summoned up today, by some on the left, who use it as a tool to thwart legitimate questions about people and ideologies that seek to destroy America. |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120811040903/http://www.thestate.com/2012/07/29/2371334/thomas-suppose-michele-bachmann.html |archivedate=11 August 2012 |df= }}</ref>\n\nResponding to her critics, Bachmann said that \"The concerns I have and my colleagues have are real,\" and \"We cannot elevate political correctness over national security.\"<ref>{{cite news |title=Bachmann shuns 'political correctness' |url=http://www.upi.com/Top_News/US/2012/07/31/Bachmann-shuns-political-correctness/UPI-94091343769420/ |newspaper=United Press International |date=31 July 2012 |accessdate=11 August 2012 |quote=While in Minnesota to observe work on the new St. Croix River bridge, Bachmann brushed off backlash over her speculation that U.S. Rep. Keith Ellison, D-Ind., and Huma Abedin, deputy chief of staff for Secretary of State Hillary Clinton, have ties to the Muslim Brotherhood.}}</ref> Rooney expressed similar concerns: \"As a member of the House Armed Services and Intelligence committees, my top priority is ensuring the security of our nation.\" And that \"I regret that Mrs. Abedin has become the media focus of this story, because the intention of the letters was to bring greater attention to the legitimate national security risk.\"<ref>{{cite news |title=Is Rep. Tom Rooney using McCarthy tactics on Muslim Brotherhood? |author=Opinion Staff |url=http://blogs.palmbeachpost.com/opinionzone/2012/07/20/is-rep-tom-rooney-using-mccarthy-tactics-on-muslim-brotherhood/ |newspaper=Palm Beach Post |date=20 July 2012 |accessdate=18 August 2012 |quote=Rep. Rooney said he was concerned about the Muslim Brotherhood's involvement in the 2009 shooting at Fort Hood, Texas, in which a Muslim Army officer murdered 13 people.}}</ref> A couple of months later, Rooney admitted that it was an unfortunate mistake to include Mrs. Abedin: \"What got lost was a legitimate question, for the sake of using Congressman (Anthony) Weiner's wife and Sec. Clinton's assistant's name specifically in a letter.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tcpalm.com/news/2012/sep/25/rooney-naming-hillary-clintons-chief-of-staff-a/|title=Rooney: Naming Hillary Clinton's chief of staff in a letter as potentially 'serious security concern' was a mistake|first=Jonathan|last=Mattise|date=25 September 2012 |work=TCPalm.com |publisher=Scripps Treasure Coast Newspapers |accessdate=28 September 2012 |quote=Rooney, R-Tequesta, reiterated the investigation's importance Tuesday, specifically regarding Department of Defense issues and the tragedy at Fort Hood.}}</ref>\n\nDuring an October campaign stop in Florida to support [[Mitt Romney]], John McCain acknowledged that Rooney and Bachmann had realized that including Abedin's name in the letter to the State Department was a mistake. McCain then softened his earlier criticism from the Senate floor, saying \"I'm concerned, and they're concerned and I agree with them, about the influence of the Muslim Brotherhood. I'm not saying all members of the Muslim Brotherhood are extremists, but I am saying there are some extremists that are members of the Muslim Brotherhood. ... There is definitely a threat of radical Muslim extremism, some of whom are Muslim Brotherhood\u2014not all, by far.\"<ref>{{cite web|last=Mattise|first=Jonathan|title=Sen. John McCain shares insights on Florida as a campaign destination, other topics|url=http://www.tcpalm.com/news/2012/oct/24/sen-john-mccain-shares-insights-on-florida-as-a/|work=TCPalm|publisher=Scripps Treasure Coast Newspapers|accessdate=26 October 2012|date=24 October 2012}}</ref>\n\n===Florida water quality===\n[[File:Florida Algae Bloom 01.jpg|thumb|A Florida kayaker's paddles scoop up algae on the Santa Fe River, 2012]]\nNitrogen and phosphorus pollution provide nutrients that can cause [[Algal bloom|algae blooms]], which in turn produce toxins harmful to humans and animals across the state of Florida. Approximately 1,900 miles of rivers and streams in the state were impaired for nutrients in 2010, up from approximately 1,000 miles in 2008. Impaired acres of lakes in Florida were 378,000 in 2010, up from 350,000 acres in 2008.<ref name=\"EPA\">{{cite web |title=Federal Water Quality Standards for the State of Florida |url=http://water.epa.gov/lawsregs/rulesregs/florida_index.cfm |work=Water: Regulatory Information|publisher=U.S. Environmental Protection Agency|accessdate=18 September 2012|date=31 July 2012}}</ref>\n\n====Background====\nIn 2008 the public interest law firm [[Earthjustice]] sued the [[United States Environmental Protection Agency|EPA]] on behalf of five environmental groups, claiming that delays by both state and federal governments in establishing quantitaive (rather than qualitative) limits for [[nutrient pollution]] of Florida's waters were unacceptable. In August 2009 the Obama administration settled the lawsuit by agreeing to begin the process of imposing enforceable EPA standards for nutrient levels in the public waters of Florida.<ref>{{cite press release |url=http://earthjustice.org/news/press/2009/epa-agrees-to-set-limits-on-fertilizer-and-animal-waste-pollution-in-florida |title=EPA Agrees to Set Limits on Fertilizer and Animal Waste Pollution in Florida |date=21 August 2009 |publisher=Earthjustice |accessdate=20 August 2012 |quote=Under the administration of President George W. Bush, the EPA let the states off the hook by allowing them to formulate plans without deadlines for action.}}</ref>\n\nNumerical nutrient level standards announced in November 2010 provoked the State of Florida to fight back by suing the EPA (enraging Earthjustice and environmentalists). Florida's outgoing ([[Bill McCollum]]) and incoming ([[Pam Bondi]]) Attorneys General, as well as the outgoing ([[Charles H. Bronson]]) and incoming ([[Adam Putnam]]) Agriculture Commissioners said that the EPA standards \"are not based on scientifically sound methodology, and were adopted in an arbitrary and capricious manner just to settle a lawsuit.\" The EPA said that the regulations would not be implemented for 15 months.<ref>{{cite news |title=Florida sues the EPA to block water pollution rules |first=Bill |last=Kaczor |url=http://www.tampabay.com/incoming/florida-sues-the-epa-to-block-water-pollution-rules/1138748 |newspaper=Tampa Bay Times |date=8 December 2010 |accessdate=20 August 2012 |quote=The case was filed in the same Pensacola federal court where McCollum also is challenging President Barack Obama's health care overhaul.}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://floridaindependent.com/16539/earthjustice-blasts-state-lawsuit-against-epa |title=Earthjustice blasts state lawsuit against EPA |first=Virginia |last=Chamlee |date=8 December 2010 |work=Florida Independent |publisher=American Independent News Network |accessdate=19 August 2012 |quote=David Guest, attorney for Earthjustice, released a statement following yesterday's announcement of the suit against the EPA. Calling the lawsuit a 'waste of taxpayer dollars,' Guest said that the state was using tax dollars to side with polluters rather than the environment.}}</ref>\n\nOne year later, Earthjustice counterattacked by filing suit against the [[Florida Department of Environmental Protection]] (FDEP) claiming that the state agency had failed to protect Floridians and tourists from toxic algae outbreaks.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://earthjustice.org/news/press/2011/earthjustice-files-suit-to-protect-floridians-right-to-clean-water |title= Earthjustice Files Suit to Protect Floridians' Right to Clean Water |date= 1 December 2011 |work= Press Release |publisher= Earthjustice |accessdate= 20 August 2012 |quote= The rule that the EPA set for Florida was a 'speed limit sign' that gave everyone fair notice of what specific level of pollution would be allowed in a particular water body. If the speed limit was exceeded, regulators could take action to prevent toxic algae outbreaks and green slime. But the DEP's rule doesn't provide that certainty, and it won't protect public health.}}</ref> Judge Bram Canter of the Florida Division of Administrative Hearings ruled against the Earthjustice lawsuit in June, 2012.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://earthjustice.org/news/press/2012/floridians-lose-in-the-fight-for-clean-water |title= Floridians Lose In the Fight For Clean Water |date= 7 June 2012 |work= Press Release |publisher= Earthjustice |accessdate= 20 August 2012 |quote= This decision represents yet another failure to address Florida's worst pollution problem\u2014sewage, manure and fertilizer in our water.}}</ref> The Obama administration then announced that EPA enforcement would be delayed until 2013, and that the EPA may defer to FDEP regulations.<ref>{{cite news |title= As the election nears, new rules are facing delays |first= Dina |last= Cappiello |url= http://www.businessweek.com/ap/2012-07-30/as-the-election-nears-new-rules-are-facing-delays |newspaper= Bloomberg Businessweek |date= 30 July 2012 |accessdate= 20 August 2012 |quote= Critics of the regulations are hoping for another election-year gift: a decision by the EPA to abandon its requirements, and instead endorse ones drafted by the state.}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title= Rules Delayed, Governing Denied |author= Editorial |url= https://www.nytimes.com/2012/08/12/opinion/sunday/rules-delayed-governing-denied.html |newspaper= New York Times |date= 11 August 2012 |accessdate= 20 August 2012 |quote= The E.P.A. itself has repeatedly postponed the effective date of... a rule hotly opposed by developers in a hotly contested state.}}</ref>\n\n====Rooney challenges EPA====\nAfter the EPA said that it would establish numeric nutrient levels for waters in the state of Florida, as part of the 2009 consent decree with Earthjustice, Rooney led the state's congressional delegation by writing a letter asking the EPA to work with the state as it formulated rules for Florida. Rooney explained:\n\n<blockquote>Florida has spent over $19 million and several years collecting the necessary data, sound science and community input to develop standards that are realistic and attainable for Florida. As the EPA begins to establish nutrient levels for Florida waters, it is important for the state to be a part of the decision process and to use the invaluable information that has been collected. This bipartisan letter signed by twenty-five members of our delegation simply asks EPA to work with Florida and utilize its data.\"<ref>{{cite web |url= http://rooney.house.gov/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=3021 |title= Rooney Heads Florida Delegation Request to EPA |date= 2 December 2009 |work= Press Release |publisher= Congressman Thomas J. Rooney Website |accessdate= 20 August 2012}}</ref></blockquote> \n\nFollowing the January 2010 publication of proposed EPA rules for Florida, Rooney said: \"There are still too many questions that must be answered regarding the science used by the EPA.\"<ref>{{cite web |url= http://rooney.house.gov/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=3007 |title= Rooney Statement on EPA Field Hearing |date= 18 February 2010 |work= Press Release |publisher= Congressman Thomas J. Rooney Website |accessdate= 20 August 2012}}</ref> Rooney and other members of Florida's Congressional delegation met with EPA Administrator Lisa Jackson in March, concerning the proposed Numeric Nutrient rules. At that meeting the agency agreed to extend the public comment period and to hold three more public meetings in Florida. Rooney also told Jackson that he was concerned, inasmuch as she had failed to meet personally with Florida Department of Environmental Protection Secretary Michael Sole. Rooney said: \"While there was progress in some areas the EPA proposal will have massive repercussions throughout our state. Therefore, this is something we cannot rush head-first into without knowing all the facts and science.\"<ref>{{cite web |url= http://rooney.house.gov/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=3005 |title= Rooney Asks for Third Party EPA Review |date= 18 February 2010 |work= Press Release |publisher= Congressman Thomas J. Rooney Website |accessdate= 21 August 2012 |quote=There has been great concern about the reliability and legitimacy of the science used by the EPA in setting the proposed numeric numbers. At this morning's meeting Rooney asked the EPA to help settle this dispute by having a third party study and review the science the agency used.}}</ref> Rooney pointed to studies concluding that the proposed rule would take $2 billion out of Florida's economy, and urged the EPA to do an economic analysis of the rule. He also called for the EPA to allow an independent, scientific review of the rule, which the EPA refused to do.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.tcpalm.com/news/2011/feb/21/tom-rooney-untested-proposed-epa-regulations-not/ |title= Untested proposed EPA regulations might not clean Florida's water, but will dramatically drive up costs for residents and businesses |first= Tom |last= Rooney |date= 21 February 2011 |work= TCPalm.com |publisher= Scripps Treasure Coast Newspapers |accessdate= 20 August 2012 |quote= I will not allow EPA to act tyrannically and dictatorially on this issue that affects every Floridian. Until the EPA is willing to consider Florida's unique needs and its economy, this regulation must not go into effect.}}</ref>\n\nAn April, 2010 report by the Florida Department of Agriculture and Consumer Services, in conjunction with professors at the University of Florida Food and Resource Economics Department, and with Soil and Water Engineering Technology, Inc. concluded that compliance with the proposed numeric nutrient rule would subject 13.6 million acres of agriculture to direct costs of from $902 million to $1.605 billion annually, and indirect economic impacts of $1.148 billion per year to the state of Florida. \"This report confirms what we have all feared. The economic ramifications of this proposed rule would be devastating to our state,\" Rooney said.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://rooney.house.gov/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=2977 |title= Rooney: Proposed EPA Numeric Nutrient Rule \"Devastating\" for Florida Economy |date= 22 April 2010 |work= Press Release |publisher= Congressman Thomas J. Rooney Website |accessdate= 21 August 2012}}\n</ref> In August, Rooney again called for delay of final federal rulemaking, pending the results of a third-party analysis, in a bipartisan letter from Florida's Congressional delegation to Lisa Jackson.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://rooney.house.gov/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=2911 |title= Rooney Calls for Independent Analysis of Numeric Nutrient Proposal |date= 1 August 2010 |work= Press Release |publisher= Congressman Thomas J. Rooney Website |accessdate= 21 August 2012}}</ref>\n\nIn September, a federal judge temporarily stopped the U.S. Army Corps of Engineers from imposing federal water quality standards on former croplands in the Everglades, ruling that the Corps had changed its rules about water quality standards on former croplands without proper public notice and hearing.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.palmbeachpost.com/news/news/state-regional/federal-judge-halts-army-corps-efforts-to-clean-up/nMBNQ/ |title= Federal judge halts Army Corps' efforts to clean up former cropland in Everglades |last= Stapleton |first= Christine |date= 29 September 2010 |newspaper= Palm Beach Post |accessdate= 3 September 2012 |quote=Nutrient standards\u2014especially in the Everglades\u2014have been especially controversial lately as two federal judges have ordered water managers and environmental officials to enforce nutrient standards and speed up the Everglades cleanup.}}</ref> In December, 2010, Florida Attorney General Bill McCollum and Attorney General-elect Pam Bondi decided to file a lawsuit against the EPA regarding its proposed numeric nutrient rule. Rooney endorsed that decision, saying that \"this lawsuit will put a stop to the EPA's misguided assaults on Florida's families and industries.\" Senator George LeMieux also endorsed the legal challenge to the EPA rule for Florida.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://rooney.house.gov/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=3121|title= Rooney, LeMieux Support Florida Lawsuit against EPA|date= 7 December 2010|work= Press Release|publisher= Congressman Thomas J. Rooney Website|accessdate= 21 August 2012}}</ref>\n\n====Cooperation, criticism and compromise====\nAfter Lisa Jackson appeared before the House Agriculture Committee in March 2011, Rooney said: \"In all the hearings I've attended as a member of Congress, I've never been to one like Lisa Jackson's appearance before the House Agriculture Committee. All the members of the committee\u2014Republicans and Democrats\u2014were up in arms over the EPA's agenda. I've never seen a witness from the administration get attacked like that from members of the president's own party.\"<ref>{{cite news|last=Ward|first=Kenric|title=EPA Boss Lisa Jackson in Hot Water Over Job-Killing Policies Florida businesses, and even Democrats, challenge chief on science, economy|url=http://www.sunshinestatenews.com/story/epa-boss-lisa-jackson-hot-water-over-job-killing-policies|accessdate=18 September 2012|newspaper=Sunshine State News|date=27 June 2011|quote=Under the leadership of Lisa Jackson, the EPA has alternately antagonized and disappointed business leaders and environmentalists.}}</ref> Rooney sent a letter thanking Jackson for her promise that the EPA would cooperate with the state of Florida (and their Congressional delegation) to come up with reasonable nutrient levels, and for allowing both scientific review and economic analysis of the new regulations. Rooney's letter also asked the following questions:<ref>{{cite web |url= http://rooney.house.gov/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=3181 |title= Rooney Thanks EPA Administrator for Commitment to Work with Florida on Numeric Nutrient Compromise |date= 11 March 2011 |work= Press Release |publisher= Congressman Thomas J. Rooney Website |accessdate= 21 August 2012}}</ref>\n* When will EPA begin to produce a complete economic analysis of the impact of the proposed regulation, and when does EPA expect that analysis to be complete?\n* What methodology will EPA use in its economic analysis?\n* Which third-party organization will EPA task with conducting a thorough review of the proposed rule?\n* When will that third-party review commence, and when does EPA expect it to conclude?\n* How will EPA adjust the proposed regulation to accommodate the findings of the third-party review and economic analysis?\n\nRooney and Senator Marco Rubio were criticised in the press for \"siding with polluters\" and \"greedy business interests,\" leading Rooney and Rubio to co-author an article explaining that \"half of the Democrats in Florida's House delegation supported our amendment to prevent the EPA from enforcing this new mandate until they complete an independent study of the science and a thorough economic analysis\" and that Lisa Jackson had recently committed to having the EPA work with Florida's DEP.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.tcpalm.com/news/2011/mar/18/editorial-rooney-and-rubio-join-forces-to-fight/ |title= Editorial: Rooney and Rubio join forces to fight EPA over clean water regulations for Florida |author= Editorial board |date= 18 March 2011 |work= TCPalm.com |publisher= Scripps Treasure Coast Newspapers |accessdate= 21 August 2012}}\n</ref><ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.tcpalm.com/news/2011/mar/29/marco-rubio-tom-rooney-why-were-fighting-the-job/ |title= Marco Rubio and Tom Rooney: Why we're fighting the EPA's job-destroying water mandate |first1= Marco |last1= Rubio |first2= Tom |last2= Rooney |date= 29 March 2011 |work= TCPalm.com |publisher= Scripps Treasure Coast Newspapers |accessdate= 21 August 2012}}</ref> Although the Rooney amendment was eventually dropped, the EPA agreed to a one-year delay of new water rules and that the [[National Academy of Sciences]] would conduct an unbiased review of the EPA cost estimate.<ref>{{cite web|title=A bipartisan effort forces EPA to delay, again, new water rules for Florida|url=http://www.tampabay.com/blogs/the-buzz-florida-politics/content/bipartisan-effort-forces-epa-delay-again-new-water-rules-florida|work=The Buzz (blog)|publisher=Tampa Bay Times|accessdate=18 September 2012|date=11 April 2011|quote=A raft of policy riders were dropped from the budget deal approved late Friday, including one that would have prevented the Environmental Protection Agency from enforcing controversial new clean water standards in Florida. But the rules are on hold anyway.}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Jackson|first=Lisa|title=Letter to Sen. Bill Nelson|url=http://www.tampabay.com/blogs/the-buzz-florida-politics/sites/tampabay.com.blogs.the-buzz-florida-politics/files/nelson.pdf|accessdate=18 September 2012|format=PDF|date=6 April 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|first=Tom|last=Rooney|url=http://rooney.house.gov/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=3207|title=Rooney: EPA Agreement to Study Cost of Numeric Nutrient Mandate a Good Start|date =11 April 2011|work=Press Release|publisher =Congressman Thomas J. Rooney Website|accessdate=21 August 2012|quote=Florida's Department of Environmental Protection, the Chamber of Commerce, the League of Cities, and the Farm Bureau, along with the EPA, all deserve to be part of this process.}}</ref>\n\nRooney was criticized in an editorial for voting for a House bill sponsored by [[John Mica]] that would prohibit tightening water pollutant limits without a state's consent, a bill that the EPA protested would \"overturn almost 40 years of federal legislation by preventing EPA from protecting public health and water quality.\"<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.tcpalm.com/news/2011/aug/01/editorial-proposal-in-us-senate-would-weaken-in/ |title= Editorial: Proposal in U.S. Senate would weaken efforts in Florida, nationwide to clean up waterways |author= Editorial board |date= 1 August 2011 |work= TCPalm.com |publisher= Scripps Treasure Coast Newspapers |accessdate= 20 August 2012|quote=Rooney, citing multiple concerns, including those about the potential cost to business and agriculture, has actively supported legislation that would block the EPA from implementing numerical limits to nitrogen and phosphorus in state waters under the federal Clean Water Act. This is disconcerting given that Rooney also portrays himself as a champion of the St. Lucie River and Indian River Lagoon.}}</ref> In an October 2011 column, Rooney justified congressional review of EPA regulations, reduction of red tape and interference with new mandates as a means to \"get the federal government off the backs of famers.\"<ref>{{cite news| url= http://www2.highlandstoday.com/news/agri-leader/2011/oct/12/LRNEWSO6-cutting-through-farm-red-tape-ar-303179/|title= Cutting through farm red tape|last=Rooney|first=Tom|date=12 October 2011|newspaper=Highlands Today|accessdate=21 August 2012|quote=...the high costs of excessive government regulation and red tape are threatening to drive farmers out of business. Small farmers, who have fewer resources to keep up with the growing number of federal mandates, are being hit especially hard.}}</ref>\n\nRooney welcomed amended rules for numeric nutrient standards, approved in December by the [[Florida Environmental Regulation Commission]] and submitted to the EPA. After final approval by the EPA, the federal standards would then be withdrawn. The EPA acknowledged that \"states have the primary role in establishing and implementing water quality standards for their waters.\"<ref name=\"EPA\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://rooney.house.gov/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=3318|title=Rooney Applauds Florida Environmental Commission Approval of Reasonable Numeric Nutrient Standards|date =8 December 2011|work=Press Release|publisher =Congressman Thomas J. Rooney Website|accessdate=21 August 2012|quote=By bringing all sides to the table, as I and others have advocated, Florida was able to reach a compromise that I think everyone can support.}}</ref> In June 2012, Florida submitted, and the EPA approved, a plan to improve water quality in the Everglades.<ref>{{cite web|title=Florida Moving Forward with Plan to Improve Water Quality in America's Everglades|url=http://depnewsroom.wordpress.com/2012/06/13/florida-moving-forward-with-plan-to-improve-water-quality-in-americas-everglades/|work=DEP News|publisher=WordPress.com|accessdate=18 September 2012|author=MsNicolePR|date=13 June 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Letter to Gwendolyn Keyes Fleming|url=http://www.dep.state.fl.us/secretary/news/2012/06/vinyard_letter_epa_admin_fleming.pdf|accessdate=18 September 2012|author=Herschel T. Vinyard Jr.|format=PDF|date=6 June 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Letter to Herschel T. Vinyard Jr.|url=http://www.dep.state.fl.us/secretary/news/2012/06/fleming_response_revised_permit_061312.pdf|accessdate=18 September 2012|author=Gwendolyn Keyes Fleming|format=PDF|date=13 June 2012}}</ref>\n\n=== Tax reform ===\n\nRooney voted in favor of the [[Tax Cuts and Jobs Act of 2017]].<ref name=\"Almukhtar\">{{cite web|last1=Almukhtar|first1=Sarah|title=How Each House Member Voted on the Tax Bill|url=https://www.nytimes.com/interactive/2017/12/19/us/politics/tax-bill-house-live-vote.html?_r=0|website=The New York Times|accessdate=24 December 2017|date=19 December 2017}}</ref> The bill includes disaster relief aid for Florida citrus growers who suffered loss due to [[Hurricane Irma]], which Rooney calls a \"big win.\"<ref name=\"FT121917\">{{cite web|title=Tuesday's Daily Pulse|url=http://www.floridatrend.com/article/23604/tuesdays-daily-pulse|website=Florida Trend|accessdate=24 December 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Gun policy===\n\nRooney characterizes himself as a \"champion for [[Second Amendment to the United States Constitution|Second Amendment]] rights,\" saying that the right to bear arms is \"one of our most sacred rights.\"<ref name=\"Rooney 2016\">{{cite web| url=http://www.tomrooney.com/single-post/2016/03/01/Protecting-the-Second-Amendment| title=Protecting the Second Amendment| date=1 March 2016| website=tomrooney.com| publisher=Tom Rooney for Congress| access-date=6 March 2018}}</ref>\nAs of 2017, Rooney has an \"A-\" rating from the [[National Rifle Association|NRA]], indicating a voting record that is generally pro-gun rights.<ref name=\"ISPY\">{{cite web| url=https://votesmart.org/candidate/107800/tom-rooney?categoryId=37&type=V,S,R,E,F,P#.Wp7tQ-dG1PY| title=Tom Rooney's Political Summary on Issue: Guns| website=ISPY| publisher=Vote Smart| access-date=6 March 2018}}</ref>\nAs a Congressman, Rooney has voted in favor of several pieces of legislation to expand gun rights, including a yes vote on [https://www.congress.gov/bill/115th-congress/house-bill/38 H. R. 38] (the Concealed Carry Reciprocity Act), which would enable [[Concealed carry in the United States#Reciprocity|concealed carry reciprocity]] among all States if and when it is signed into law.<ref name=\"HR38\">{{cite web| url=http://clerk.house.gov/evs/2017/roll663.xml| title=FINAL VOTE RESULTS FOR ROLL CALL 663| website=clerk.house.gov|publisher=U.S. Federal Government|date=6 December 2017| access-date=5 March 2018}}</ref>\nOf the Act, Rooney said, \"Just as a driver's license would be recognized in another state, a person who is legally permitted to carry a concealed handgun for their or their loved ones' own protection should have that ability anywhere in our nation.\"<ref name=\"Rooney 2017\">{{cite web| url=https://rooney.house.gov/media-center/press-releases/rooney-house-pass-national-concealed-carry-reciprocity-act| title=Rooney, House Pass National Concealed Carry Reciprocity Act| website=Thomas J. Rooney| publisher=U. S. Federal Government}}</ref>\nIn March 2017, Rooney voted in favor of the [https://www.congress.gov/bill/115th-congress/house-bill/1181 Veterans Second Amendment Protection Act], which, if signed into law, will allow [[veteran]]s who are considered \"mentally incompetent\" to purchase ammunition and firearms unless declared a danger by a judge.<ref name=\"HR 1181\">{{cite web| url=http://clerk.house.gov/evs/2017/roll169.xml| title=FINAL VOTE RESULTS FOR ROLL CALL 169| website=clerk.house.gov|publisher=U.S. Federal Government|date=16 March 2017| access-date=5 March 2018}}</ref>\nRooney also voted in favor of [https://www.congress.gov/bill/115th-congress/house-joint-resolution/40 H.J.Res.40], which successfully used the [[Congressional Review Act]] to [[Repeal of the Implementation of the NICS Improvement Amendments Act of 2007|block implementation]] of an Obama-era Amendment to the [[NICS Improvement Amendments Act of 2007]] that was aimed at preventing the mentally-infirm from legally purchasing firearms.<ref name=\"Clerk 2017\">{{cite web| url=http://clerk.house.gov/evs/2017/roll077.xml| website=clerk.house.gov|publisher=U. S. Federal Government| date=2 February 2017| access-date=6 March 2018| title=FINAL VOTE RESULTS FOR ROLL CALL 77}}</ref>\n\nIn 2015, Rooney signed a letter to the [[Bureau of Alcohol, Tobacco, Firearms and Explosives]] objecting to a proposed ban of [[.223 Remington|a certain rifle cartridge]] due to its [[Armor-piercing shell#Small arms|armor-piercing]] capabilities.<ref name=\"ATF 2015\">{{cite web| url=https://woodall.house.gov/sites/woodall.house.gov/files/ATFLETTER.pdf| title=Letter to B. Todd Jones, Director of the Bureau of Alcohol, Tobacco, Firearms and Explosives - Ammunition Ban| date=4 March 2015| website=Congressman Rob Woodall| publisher=U. S. Federal Government| access-date=6 March 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"Date 2015\">{{cite web| title=ATF Director B. Todd Jones Stepping Down After Nearly 4 Years on Job | url=http://abcnews.go.com/Politics/atf-director-todd-jones-stepping-years-job/story?id=29779602| last1=Date| first1=Jack| last2=Levine| first2=Mike| date=20 March 2015}}</ref>\nIn the letter, it states that \"the idea that Congress intended [https://www.congress.gov/bill/99th-congress/house-bill/3132 LEOPA] to ban one of the preeminent rifle cartridges in use by Americans for legitimate purposes is preposterous.\"<ref name=\"ATF 2015\"/>\nThe attempt to ban the cartridges was abandoned shortly thereafter.<ref name=\"Date 2015\"/>\n\nRooney opened up more about his opinions on gun [[lobbying|lobbyist]] groups after his February 2018 announcement that he would not be seeking reelection.\nRooney stated that even supporting a [[Bump fire#Bump fire stocks|bump stock]] ban after the [[2017 Las Vegas shooting]] was akin to \"political suicide\" and that \"the NRA has an extremely sophisticated ability to either help you or hurt you from being able to continue to call yourself 'Congressman.'\"<ref name=\"Cerabino 2018\">{{cite news| url=https://www.mypalmbeachpost.com/news/cerabino-fla-congressman-reveals-nra-scorecard-not-the-whole-score/xCyiZ53GJ7uZCkMzwYsK5N/| title=Cerabino: Fla. Congressman reveals NRA scorecard not the whole score| last=Cerabino| first=Frank| work=Palm Beach Post| location=Palm Beach County, Florida| access-date=6 March 2018}}</ref>\nRooney also questioned the role of [[AR-15 style rifle]]s in society, saying \"What is the purpose of that gun, especially one with a bump stock on it?\"<ref name=\"Cerabino 2018\"/>\n\n==Personal life==\nTom Rooney is a grandson of Pittsburgh Steelers founder [[Art Rooney]] Sr.,<ref>[http://www.tcpalm.com/news/2009/jan/18/are-you-ready-for-smashmouth-football/ Rep. Tom Rooney: Are you ready for some smashmouth football?]</ref> a nephew of [[Pittsburgh Steelers]] owner and ambassador to Ireland [[Dan Rooney]],<ref name=\"Semnani\"/> and a first cousin, once removed, of actresses [[Kate Mara]] and [[Rooney Mara]].<ref name=\"Semnani\">{{cite news |title=Heard on the Hill: Six Degrees of Tom Rooney |first=Neda |last=Semanani |url=http://www.rollcall.com/issues/57_78/heard_hill_six_degrees_tom_rooney-211393-1.html |newspaper=Roll Call |date=9 January 2012 |accessdate=8 August 2012 |quote=The Florida Republican is related to, um, maybe everyone on the Eastern Seaboard, or at least most everyone involved in the National Football League.}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.geni.com/blog/family-tree-tuesday-rooney-mara-375297.html |title=Rooney Mara |author=Hiromimarie |date=5 June 2012 |work=Family Tree Tuesday |publisher=Geni Blog |accessdate=8 August 2012 |quote=Mara is the great-granddaughter of both New York Giants founder Tim Mara and Pittsburgh Steelers founder Art Rooney, Sr.}}</ref>\n\nRooney's younger brother, Brian J. Rooney, has a seat on the Pittsburgh Steelers Board of Directors which was previously held by their father. Brian, a veteran of the Iraq War, is a Deputy Director of [[Michigan Department of Human Services]], and was a candidate in 2010 for Congress in [[Michigan's 7th congressional district]].<ref>\n{{cite web |url=http://www.postonpolitics.com/2010/04/burn-notice-gops-west-raises-and-spends-big-in-klein-challenge/ |title=Burn notice: GOP's West raises and spends big in Klein challenge |last=Bennett |first=George |date=16 April 2010 |work=Post On Politics Blog |publisher=Palm Beach Post |accessdate=8 August 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Brian Rooney Deputy Director, Policy and Compliance|url=http://www.michigan.gov/dhs/0,1687,7-124-5459_62220-282497--,00.html|work=Department of Human Services|publisher=Michigan.gov|accessdate=26 October 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Gautz|first=Chris|title=Governor-elect Rick Snyder taps former Brian Rooney, former 7th District GOP candidate, to help lead Human Services Department|url=http://www.mlive.com/news/jackson/index.ssf/2010/12/snyder_taps_former_brian_roone.html|accessdate=26 October 2012|newspaper=Jackson Citizen Patriot|date=30 December 2010}}</ref> Tom's older brother, [[Patrick Rooney, Jr.]], serves in the Florida House of Representatives in District 83.<ref>\n{{cite news |title=Tom and Pat aren't the only Rooney candidates |first=George |last=Bennett |url=http://www.palmbeachpost.com/news/news/tom-and-pat-arent-the-only-rooney-candidates/nL4fr/ |newspaper=Palm Beach Post |date=15 February 2012 |accessdate=8 August 2012 |quote=Four other Rooney siblings are not seeking office.}}</ref><ref>\n{{cite web|url=http://www.myfloridahouse.gov/sections/representatives/details.aspx?MemberId=4516&SessionId=66|work=Patrick Rooney, Jr. Biography|accessdate=6 August 2011|title=Florida House of Representatives}}</ref>\n\nTom, Tara and their three sons (Tommy, Sean, Seamus) formerly split their time between Tequesta, Florida and Washington,  D.C.<ref name=\"About\">{{cite web |url=http://rooney.house.gov/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=3081 |title=About Tom |work=Congressional Website |accessdate=8 August 2012}}</ref> Rooney decided to run in the new District 17, and he promised to move into that district, but told ''[[The Ledger]]'' that he and his wife had not yet decided on which city.<ref>{{cite news |title=The Ledger Recommends \u2013 U.S. Representative Dist. 17: Tom Rooney  |url=http://www.theledger.com/article/20120806/EDIT01/120809676/-1/news22 |newspaper=The Ledger |date=6 August 2012 |accessdate=8 August 2012}}</ref> Rooney planned to move to [[Charlotte County, Florida|Charlotte County]], but he said that \"I'm leaving where I grew up. That's the hardest thing.\"<ref name=\"Reshuffle\"/> Charlotte County has the largest percentage of voters in the newly-drawn district, and includes the city of [[Punta Gorda, Florida|Punta Gorda]] (where Rooney has his campaign office and one of his Congressional offices) as well as the larger, but unincorporated [[Port Charlotte, Florida|Port Charlotte]] as well as other unincorporated communities.<ref name=\"About\"/><ref>{{cite web |url=http://tomrooney.com/connect.php |title=Connect |work=Tom Rooney for Congress |accessdate=13 August 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Anderson|first=Zac|title=Rep. Rooney says he's willing to compromise to reach debt deal|url=http://politics.heraldtribune.com/2012/10/31/rep-rooney-says-hes-willing-to-compromise-to-reach-debt-deal/|accessdate=1 November 2012|newspaper=Sarasota Herald-Tribune|date=31 October 2012|quote=The 41-year-old Republican from Palm Beach County is a heavy favorite to win a third term in a newly drawn district that sprawls across the state to include part of Manatee County and all of Charlotte. Rooney's sense of urgency stems from his belief that the country is running out of time to address the national debt.}}</ref> The Rooneys ended up selling their Tequesta home and purchasing a home in [[Okeechobee, Florida|Okeechobee]].\n\n===Palm Beach Kennel Club===\nTom's grandfather, Art Rooney, bought the Palm Beach Kennel Club in West Palm Beach in 1969 and his father ran the business as president from 1984 until recently, when his brother, Patrick J. Rooney Jr., became president of the club.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://articles.sun-sentinel.com/2008-08-16/news/0808150281_1_charlie-crist-gambling-interests-endorsement |title= Crist backs Rooney for Congress |first= Jim |last= Turner |date= 16 August 2008 |work= Sun Sentinel |publisher= Scripps Treasure Coast Newspapers |accessdate= 2 September 2012 |quote=As part of the growing bitterness in the race, the Kennel Club's president, Pat Rooney Sr., the candidate's father, has threatened Valeche with a lawsuit over a newspaper editorial in which Valeche criticized the kennel club's proposal to expand gambling.}}</ref><ref name=\"Family\">{{cite news |url=http://www.palmbeachpost.com/news/sports/rooney-family-has-made-a-big-impact-in-palm-beach-/nLphQ/ |title= Rooney family has made a big impact in Palm Beach County |first= Brian |last= Biggane |date= 3 February 2011 |newspaper= Palm Beach Post |accessdate= 2 September 2012 |quote=PBKC remained the main family business here. Last year, it was the nation's No. 1 dog track in terms of money wagered at $199 million counting both live and simulcast.}}</ref> Tom Rooney lists ownership of stock in family businesses in his congressional financial disclosure form. Rooney has said that he has neither operational nor ownership responsibilities, and the stock is part of a trust with his children as beneficiaries.<ref>{{cite news |url= http://www.palmbeachpost.com/news/news/palm-beach-county-voters-will-decide-on-slots-in-n/nL2b9/ |title= Palm Beach County voters will decide on slots in November |last= Abramson |first= Andrew |date= 20 December 2011 |newspaper= Palm Beach Post |accessdate= 18 August 2012}}</ref> In 2010, Rooney stood at 346th place in terms of net worth among the members of the U.S. House.<ref>{{cite web |url=  |title=In wealth, only 1 of 3 Treasure Coast House members in upper half |work= TCPalm.com |first= Trish |last= Choates |date= 17 March 2010 |publisher= Scripps Treasure Coast Newspapers |quote=In 2008, Rooney drew an income of $88,860 with the Stuart law firm of Kramer, Sopko and Levenstein, his 14.3 percent shares with the Patrick J. Rooney Jr. Irrevocable Trust, which owns the Palm Beach Kennel Club, the Patrick J. Rooney Sr. family trust, and a family trust involved in real estate development in Pittsburgh, are worth a combined $166,004 to $415,000.}}</ref>\n\nThe Palm Beach Kennel Club serves the product of yet another family business, Rooney's Old Irish Ale.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://articles.sun-sentinel.com/2008-08-16/news/0808150281_1_charlie-crist-gambling-interests-endorsement |title= Frequently Asked Questions |work= Rooney's Beer |publisher= Rooney's Beer Co., LLC, Pittsburgh, PA. |accessdate= 2 September 2012 |quote=From'99 to present, the Rooney's Old Irish Ale has been served and enjoyed exclusively at Florida family businesses: Rooney's Public House (Jupiter, FL), Rooney's Public House (PB International Airport), Rooney's All-In Sports Bar & Grille, (West Palm Beach, FL) and the Palm Beach Kennel Club (West Palm Beach, FL).}}</ref> The Palm Beach County Commission has approved a referendum for the November 2012 ballot to decide whether [[slot machine]]s will be allowed at the Palm Beach Kennel Club.<ref>{{cite news |url= http://articles.sun-sentinel.com/2011-12-20/news/fl-slots-referendum-palm-20111220_1_slot-full-fledged-casinos-gambling |title= Palm Beach County to hold slot machine referendum |last= Reid |first= Andy |date= 20 December 2011 |newspaper= Sun Sentinel |accessdate= 18 August 2012 |quote=The kennel club owners, the influential Rooney family, have lobbied for years to get slot machines and other expanded gaming.}}</ref> Tom's cousin Joe Rooney is a spokesman for, as well as Co-Chair and Treasurer of the coalition supporting the Palm Beach County slot machines referendum.<ref name=\"Family\"/><ref>{{cite web|title=Leadership Team|url=http://www.voteyesforslots.com/about-us/leadership-team/|work=Vote Yes for Slot Machines in Palm Beach County|publisher=Coalition for More Jobs, Better Schools and a Stronger Economy|accessdate=24 September 2012}}</ref> Other Florida counties have put slot machine referendums on the November ballot, but Attorney General Palm Bondi issued an opinion that current state law does not allow slots outside of Miami-Dade and Broward counties.<ref>{{cite news|title=Group hopes to bring slot machines to Palm Beach County|url=http://www.wpbf.com/news/south-florida/Palm-Beach-County-News/Group-hopes-to-bring-slot-machines-to-Palm-Beach-County/-/8815578/16651428/-/format/rsss_2.0/-/y9h96qz/-/index.html|accessdate=24 September 2012|newspaper=WPBF-TV|date=18 September 2012}}</ref>  Joe Rooney said Palm Beach County will have several paths to follow if the referendum succeeds, including legislation and legal action.<ref>{{cite news|last=Sortal|first=Nick|title=Palm Beach Kennel Club revs up slot campaign|url=http://articles.sun-sentinel.com/2012-09-19/entertainment/sfl-palm-beach-kennel-club-revs-up-slot-campaign-20120919_1_slot-campaign-palm-beach-kennel-club-tax-revenue|accessdate=24 September 2012|newspaper=Sun Sentinel|date=19 September 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Movies==\nIn 2014 Rooney made a cameo appearance as a farmer in [[Walt Before Mickey]] starring [[Thomas Ian Nicholas]], [[Jon Heder]], and [[Armando Gutierrez]].\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Tom Rooney}}\n* [https://rooney.house.gov Congressman Tom Rooney] official U.S. House site\n* [http://www.tomrooney.com/ Tom Rooney for Congress]\n* {{Dmoz|Regional/North_America/United_States/Florida/Government/Federal/US_House/Tom_Rooney_%5BR-17%5D|Tom Rooney}}\n* {{C-SPAN|thomasrooney}}\n* {{CongLinks | congbio=R000583 | votesmart=107800 | fec=H8FL16022 | congress=thomas-rooney/R000583 }}<!--\nLinks formerly displayed via the CongLinks template:\n* [http://ballotpedia.org/Thomas_J._Rooney Biography] at [[Ballotpedia]]\n* [http://www.nndb.com/people/645/000180105 Biography] at [[NNDB]]\n* [http://www.govtrack.us/congress/members/412311 Congressional profile] at [[GovTrack]]\n* [http://www.opencongress.org/people/show/412311 Congressional profile] at [[Participatory Politics Foundation|OpenCongress]]\n* [http://www.rollcall.com/members/29247.html Congressional profile] at ''[[Roll Call]]''\n* [http://www.politifact.com/personalities/tom-rooney Fact-checking] at [[PolitiFact.com]]\n* [http://www.opensecrets.org/politicians/summary.php?cid=N